('business:1-4-business-aims-objectives:match:544bb729', 'business', 'business:1-4-business-aims-objectives', '1.4 Aims and Objectives', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “PLC (Public Limited Company)”?", "options": ["A business''s sales expressed as a percentage of total sales in its market or industry.", "A business whose shares are traded on the stock exchange; shareholders expect profit and growth.", "The goals a business aims to achieve, such as profit, survival, growth, market share, or providing a service.", "When a business becomes larger, for example by increasing sales, opening more outlets, or taking over a competitor."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "“PLC (Public Limited Company)” means: A business whose shares are traded on the stock exchange; shareholders expect profit and growth."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-4-business-aims-objectives:match:0e76e25c', 'business', 'business:1-4-business-aims-objectives', '1.4 Aims and Objectives', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Sole Trader”?", "options": ["A business whose shares are traded on the stock exchange; shareholders expect profit and growth.", "Prioritising customer satisfaction and meeting customer needs, even if it means making less profit.", "A business owned and run by one person; objectives are often personal, such as satisficing or service.", "The way a business develops and changes over time in terms of size, products, location, or methods."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Sole Trader” means: A business owned and run by one person; objectives are often personal, such as satisficing or service."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:exam:af20ffc4', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "What is a benefit to the local community of a nearby carpet factory extending its operating hours?", "options": ["A wider choice of carpet designs will be available", "Increased road congestion from more lorries delivering textiles", "More job opportunities will be created", "The business will pay higher taxes"], "hint": "Think about what the local community values — focus on people who live nearby, not on customers or the government.", "starter": "The benefit to the local community is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — More job opportunities will be created</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Extending operating hours means the factory needs more workers, creating employment for local residents. Job creation is a key benefit the local community wants from nearby businesses.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong stakeholder:</strong> A wider choice of carpet designs benefits customers, not the local community specifically. The local community does not gain from product variety.</li><li><strong>B — Negative impact:</strong> Increased road congestion is a <em>drawback</em> of the factory extending hours, not a benefit. This would make local residents'' lives worse.</li><li><strong>D — Wrong stakeholder:</strong> Higher tax payments benefit the government''s budget, not the local community directly. The local community is a separate stakeholder group.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:exam:4f916996', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "What impacts are a customer boycott MOST likely to have on a business?", "options": ["External growth, reduced profit, increased dividends", "Fewer customers, reduced profit, increased market share", "Improved brand image, more customers, increased profit", "Worsened reputation, lower sales, reduced profit"], "hint": "Think about what happens when customers stop buying from a business — follow the chain of effects.", "starter": "A customer boycott would most likely lead to..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — Worsened reputation, lower sales, reduced profit</h5><p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> A boycott means customers deliberately stop buying. This leads directly to fewer sales (lower revenue), damages the business''s public image (worsened reputation), and ultimately reduces profit as income falls.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> External growth would mean the business is expanding — the opposite of what a boycott causes. Increased dividends require higher profits, which a boycott would reduce.</li><li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> A boycott means fewer customers, which is partially correct, but it reduces market share (not increases it) as rival businesses gain customers who leave.</li><li><strong>C — Completely wrong:</strong> A boycott damages brand image, reduces customers and cuts profit. This option describes the exact opposite of a boycott''s effect.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:exam:52f16fdf', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a method by which government as a stakeholder can affect business activity?", "options": ["Increasing the taxation on business profits", "Giving grants to businesses to help new developments", "Increasing the number of MPs in parliament", "Spending money on new road projects"], "hint": "Which of these options is about the internal workings of parliament rather than a direct economic policy affecting business?", "starter": "The method that is NOT a way government affects business is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Increasing the number of MPs in parliament</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> The number of MPs in parliament is a political/electoral matter. It does not directly change the tax burden, regulations, spending or support available to businesses, so it is not a method by which government affects business as a stakeholder.</p><p><strong>Why the other options ARE genuine methods:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A:</strong> Increasing corporation tax directly reduces business profits and the money available for investment or dividends.</li><li><strong>B:</strong> Grants provide businesses with financial support to grow or establish themselves — directly affecting business activity.</li><li><strong>D:</strong> Government infrastructure spending on roads, railways and defence creates business opportunities and stimulates economic activity.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:exam:5db2443b', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "The directors of a public limited company have decided to reduce the size of the workforce to increase profits. Which stakeholder is MOST likely to benefit from this decision?", "options": ["Customers", "Employees", "Owners", "The local community"], "hint": "If the company makes more profit as a result of this decision, who directly receives that benefit?", "starter": "The stakeholder most likely to benefit is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Owners</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Reducing the workforce cuts wage costs. Lower costs mean higher profit margins. In a public limited company, higher profits lead to larger dividends for shareholders (the owners). This directly benefits the owners of the business.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Customers:</strong> Customers are not directly affected by a workforce reduction in terms of what they gain financially. They may even be negatively affected if service quality falls.</li><li><strong>B — Employees:</strong> Employees are directly harmed by this decision — those made redundant lose their jobs and income. Remaining employees may face increased workloads.</li><li><strong>D — Local community:</strong> More unemployment in the area is a negative consequence for the local community, not a benefit. Fewer people in work means reduced local spending and potentially increased social problems.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:exam:d41b0e27', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "A bakery manufactures and supplies a range of bread loaves to local supermarkets. Which of the following is the MOST likely effect of the bakery employees refusing to work?", "options": ["Deliveries to supermarkets will be disrupted", "Different ingredients will be used to make the bread loaves", "More bread loaves will be produced", "The bread market will become segmented"], "hint": "If workers go on strike and stop working, what is the immediate operational consequence for the bakery''s customers (the supermarkets)?", "starter": "The most likely effect of employees refusing to work is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: A — Deliveries to supermarkets will be disrupted</h5><p><strong>Why A is correct:</strong> If employees go on strike (refuse to work), bread cannot be produced. Without production, there is nothing to deliver, so supermarket deliveries will be disrupted. This demonstrates the power employees have over business operations.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>B:</strong> A strike does not cause a change in ingredients. Ingredients are decided by management, not employee action.</li><li><strong>C:</strong> This is the exact opposite. If employees refuse to work, production stops — fewer, not more, bread loaves are produced.</li><li><strong>D:</strong> Market segmentation is a marketing strategy about targeting different customer groups. It has no connection to employees refusing to work.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:exam:0db5f957', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q12", "question": "Which of the following is an internal stakeholder of a business that trades as a partnership?", "options": ["A customer", "A shareholder", "A supplier", "An employee"], "hint": "Remember: internal stakeholders are those INSIDE the business. Also remember that partnerships do NOT have shareholders — only limited companies do.", "starter": "An internal stakeholder of a partnership is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — An employee</h5><p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> An employee works within the business, making them an internal stakeholder. This applies to any business structure, including a partnership.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Customer:</strong> Customers are external stakeholders — they exist outside the business and buy from it.</li><li><strong>B — Shareholder:</strong> A partnership does NOT have shareholders. Shareholders only exist in limited companies (Ltd and plc). This is a deliberate exam trap to see if students know the difference between business types and stakeholders.</li><li><strong>C — Supplier:</strong> Suppliers are external stakeholders — they provide goods or services to the business from outside.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:exam:88f980c3', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q13", "question": "Which of the following are the customers of a business MOST likely to be interested in?", "options": ["Employee wages", "Job security", "Product range", "Share dividends"], "hint": "Think about what you care about as a customer when you go shopping. What would make you choose one business over another?", "starter": "Customers are most likely to be interested in..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Product range</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Customers are primarily interested in what the business sells — the quality, price, range and availability of products and services. A wider product range gives customers more choice and increases the chance they will find what they need.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Employee wages:</strong> This is an objective of employees, not customers. Customers are generally not affected by what workers are paid, unless ethical concerns about pay are involved.</li><li><strong>B — Job security:</strong> This is an objective of employees. Customers do not have a personal stake in whether a business''s workers keep their jobs.</li><li><strong>D — Share dividends:</strong> Dividends are paid to shareholders/owners. Customers are not shareholders (unless they happen to own shares separately), and dividends do not affect the price or quality of what customers buy.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:0923ddc2', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is the correct definition of a stakeholder?", "options": ["Someone who objects to a business development they do not like", "A person or group of people who have an interest in business activity", "A person or group who always support business activity", "Someone who owns shares in a limited company"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: A stakeholder is any person or group with an interest in a business — this includes owners, employees, customers, suppliers, government and the local community. They do not have to agree with or support the business to be a stakeholder. Option D describes a shareholder specifically, which is only one type of stakeholder."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:89b116dc', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is an INTERNAL stakeholder?", "options": ["A customer", "A supplier", "An employee", "The local community"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: Internal stakeholders are those who are part of the business itself — owners and employees. Customers, suppliers and the local community are all external stakeholders because they exist outside the business. A is external (they buy from the business). B is external (they supply to the business). D is external (they live near but are not part of the business)."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:af20ffc4', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is a benefit to the local community of a nearby carpet factory extending its operating hours?", "options": ["A wider choice of carpet designs will be available", "Increased road congestion from more lorries delivering textiles", "More job opportunities will be created", "The business will pay higher taxes"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: Longer operating hours means the factory needs more workers, creating more job opportunities for local residents — this is a benefit to the local community. Option A relates to customers, not the local community specifically. Option B is a negative impact (congestion is a drawback). Option D may occur but it benefits the government more than the local community directly."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:8b004d9a', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What impacts is a customer boycott MOST likely to have on a business?", "options": ["External growth, reduced profit, increased dividends", "Fewer customers, reduced profit, increased market share", "Improved brand image, more customers, increased profit", "Worsened reputation, lower sales, reduced profit"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Correct answer: A boycott means customers refuse to buy from the business. This leads to fewer sales (lower revenue), a worsened public reputation, and ultimately reduced profit. Option A is wrong — a boycott shrinks the business, not grows it. Option B is wrong — a boycott reduces market share, not increases it. Option C is completely wrong — a boycott damages brand image."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:52f16fdf', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is NOT a method by which government as a stakeholder can affect business activity?", "options": ["Increasing the taxation on business profits", "Giving grants to businesses to help new developments", "Increasing the number of MPs in parliament", "Spending money on new road projects"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: Increasing the number of MPs in parliament is a political/electoral matter and does not directly affect how businesses operate. The other three options are all genuine ways government influences business: taxation changes affect profitability (A), grants support new businesses (B), and government infrastructure spending boosts business activity (D)."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:b33ee6b3', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is NOT an external stakeholder?", "options": ["The local community", "An employee", "A supplier", "A customer of the business"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: An employee is an INTERNAL stakeholder — they work inside the business. All other options (local community, supplier, customer) are external stakeholders because they exist outside the business itself."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:5db2443b', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The directors of a public limited company have decided to reduce the size of the workforce to increase profits. Which stakeholder is MOST likely to benefit from this decision?", "options": ["Customers", "Employees", "Owners", "The local community"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: Reducing the workforce cuts wage costs, which increases profit margins. Owners (shareholders) benefit through higher dividends and increased share value. Employees (B) are directly harmed — some lose their jobs. Customers (A) do not directly benefit from this internal cost-cutting decision. The local community (D) is negatively affected by increased local unemployment."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:0db5f957', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is an internal stakeholder of a business that trades as a partnership?", "options": ["A customer", "A shareholder", "A supplier", "An employee"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Correct answer: An employee works within the business, making them an internal stakeholder. A customer (A) and supplier (C) are external stakeholders. Crucially, a partnership does NOT have shareholders (B) — only limited companies have shareholders. This is a common exam trap: do not confuse stakeholders with shareholders, especially for sole traders and partnerships."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:0b5fa2c2', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following are customers of a business MOST likely to be interested in?", "options": ["Employee wages", "Job security", "Product range", "Share dividends"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: Customers are primarily interested in price, quality, and product range — things that affect their purchasing decision. Employee wages (A) and job security (B) are objectives of employees, not customers. Share dividends (D) are the concern of shareholders/owners."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:f3a8e7e3', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is MOST likely effect of bakery employees refusing to work?", "options": ["Deliveries to supermarkets will be disrupted", "Different ingredients will be used to make the bread loaves", "More bread loaves will be produced", "The bread market will become segmented"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Correct answer: If employees go on strike (refuse to work), production stops and deliveries to supermarket customers will be disrupted. This demonstrates the power employees have over business operations. Option B is incorrect — a strike does not change ingredients. Option C is the opposite of what happens. Option D is completely unrelated to a workforce dispute."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business:mcq:08ce90bd', 'business', 'business:1-5-stakeholders-in-business', '1.5 Stakeholders in Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "JLR has not given employees a pay rise for three consecutive years. Employees have contacted their trade union. Which stakeholder group is directly taking action here?", "options": ["Customers", "Suppliers", "Employees", "Local community"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: The employees are the stakeholder group taking action by contacting their trade union. This is an example of how employees can influence business activity — through negotiation, collective bargaining or strike action — to try to achieve their objective of fair wages."}'::jsonb)
